<section xml:id="law_of_sines">
  <title>The Law of Sines</title>
  <introduction>
    <p>
      Recall <xref ref="exmp-gift-for-mau"/> in <xref ref="inverse_trigonometry"/> where Alingano Maisu is sailing to her new home in Satawal. For the first leg of the voyage, we calculated that to sail from Johnston Atoll to Majuro, you would need to head towards House ʻĀina Kona (<m>27.4^{\circ}</m>). However, in reality, currents can push the waʻa off course. Let's consider a scenario where a current of 1 knot is flowing in the direction of the house Komohana (West). If we were to face Majuro and sail straight, the current would push us to the west of our destination. To ensure we arrive at Majuro, our apparent heading will need to be adjusted accordingly, as illustrated below.
    </p>
    <image xml:id="fig-maisu-currents">
      <latex-image>
        \begin{tikzpicture}\node[below left, yshift=0.2cm] at (-11,-5.75) {Majuro};
        \node[below] at (1,-0.5) {Johnston Atoll};
        \draw[line width=1pt] (0,0) -- (-11,-5.75) node[midway,sloped,above,yshift=0.1cm] {actual course};
        \draw[line width=1pt] (0,0) -- (-8.5,-5.75) node[midway,sloped,below,yshift=-0.1cm] {apparent heading};
        \draw[line width=1pt,stealth-] (-11,-5.75) -- (-8.5,-5.75) node[midway,below,yshift=-0.1cm] {current};
        \draw[dashed] (-3,0) -- (0,0);
        \draw ([shift=(180:2)]0,0) arc (180:207.597295869:2) node[midway,right,xshift=-28,yshift=-1] {\(27.4^{\circ}\)};
        \draw ([shift=(207.597295869:2)]0,0) arc (207.597295869:214.07719528:2) node[midway,right,xshift=-1,yshift=-8] {\(C\)};
        \draw ([shift=(207.597295869:-1cm)]0,0) pic {waa1-top={waacolor}{117.597295869}{0.1}};
        \draw (-9,-5.75) arc (180:34.0771952801:0.5) node[midway,above,xshift=5,yshift=2] {\(B\)};
        \draw (-10.25,-5.75) arc (0:27.5972958686:0.75) node[midway,right,xshift=2,yshift=2] {\(A\)};\end{tikzpicture}
      </latex-image>
    </image>
    <p>
      Now, suppose we sail at 5 knots. What heading should we aim for to compensate for a 2-knot current? We note that by alternate interior angles, <m>A=27.4^{\circ}</m>. Let's represent this situation with a triangle where the sides represent speed of the waʻa and the current, allowing us to disregard the distance traveled.
    </p>
    <image xml:id="fig-maisu-triangle">
      <latex-image>
        \begin{tikzpicture}
        \draw[line width=1pt] (0,0) -- (-11,-5.75) node[midway,sloped,above,yshift=0.1cm] {\(b\)};
        \draw[line width=1pt] (0,0) -- (-8.5,-5.75) node[midway,sloped,below,yshift=-0.1cm] {\(a=5\)};
        \draw[line width=1pt] (-11,-5.75) -- (-8.5,-5.75) node[midway,below,yshift=-0.1cm] {\(c=1\)};
        \node[above] at (0,0) {\(C\)};
        \node[left] at (-11,-5.75) {\(A=27.4^{\circ}\)};
        \node[right] at (-8.25,-5.75) {\(B\)};
        \end{tikzpicture}
      </latex-image>
    </image>
    <p>
      It's important to note that this triangle is not a right triangle; instead, it's classified as an <term>oblique triangle</term>,<idx><h>oblique triangle</h></idx> meaning it does not have any right angles. Triangles can be further categorized as either <em>obtuse</em> or <em>acute</em>. An <term>obtuse triangle</term><idx><h>obtuse triangle</h></idx> contains one angle greater than <m>90^{\circ}</m>, while an <term>acute triangle</term><idx><h>acute triangle</h></idx> consists of all angles less than <m>90^{\circ}</m>. Solving such triangles requires different methods than those used for solving the right triangle in previous chapters. In this chapter, we'll learn techniques for solving oblique triangles, starting with the Law of Sines and the Law of Cosines.
    </p>
    <p>
      To solve an oblique triangle, we need to be given three pieces of information, which can take the following forms:
      <ol>
          <li>
              <p>One side and two angles.</p>
              <p>
                <ul>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      <em>Angle-Side-Angle (ASA)</em>: Two angles and the side between them are known.
                    </p>
                    <image xml:id="fig-triangle-angle-side-angle">
                      <latex-image>
                        \begin{tikzpicture}
                        \draw[blue, dashed] (0,0) -- (3,4); 
                        \draw[blue, dashed] (3,4) -- (10,0); 
                        \draw[blue, line width=1] (10,0) -- (0,0) node[midway,below] {\(S\)}; \draw[blue, line width=1] (1,0) arc (0:53.1301023542:1) node[midway,right,xshift=2,yshift=2] {\(A\)}; 
                        \draw[blue, line width=1] (9,0) arc (180:150.255118703:1) node[midway,right,xshift=-18,yshift=2] {\(A\)};
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                      </latex-image>
                    </image>
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      <em>Side-Angle-Angle (SAA)</em>: One side and two consecutive angles are known.
                    </p>
                    <image xml:id="fig-triangle-side-angle-angle">
                      <latex-image>
                        \begin{tikzpicture}
                        \draw[blue, line width=1] (0,0) -- (3,4) node[midway,left,xshift=-4] {\(S\)};
                        \draw[blue, dashed] (3,4) -- (10,0);
                        \draw[blue, dashed] (10,0) -- (0,0);
                        \draw[blue, line width=1] (1,0) arc (0:53.1301023542:1) node[midway,right,xshift=2,yshift=2] {\(A\)};
                        \draw[blue, line width=1] (9,0) arc (180:150.255118703:1) node[midway,right,xshift=-18,yshift=2] {\(A\)};
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                      </latex-image>
                    </image>
                  </li>
              </ul>
              </p>
          </li>
          <li>
              <p>Two sides and one angle.</p>
              <p>
                <ul>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      <em>Side-Side-Angle (SSA)</em>: Two sides and the angle that is not between them are known.
                    </p>
                    <image xml:id="fig-triangle-side-side-angle">
                      <latex-image>
                        \begin{tikzpicture}\draw[blue, line width=1] (0,0) -- (3,4) node[midway,above,xshift=-4] {\(S\)};
                        \draw[blue, line width=1] (3,4) -- (10,0) node[midway,above,xshift=2] {\(S\)};
                        \draw[blue, dashed] (10,0) -- (0,0);
                        \draw[blue, line width=1] (1,0) arc (0:53.1301023542:1) node[midway,right,xshift=2,yshift=2] {\(A\)};
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                      </latex-image>
                    </image>
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      <em>Side-Angle-Side (SAS)</em>: Two sides and the angle between them are known.
                    </p>
                    <image xml:id="fig-triangle-side-angle-side">
                      <latex-image>
                        \begin{tikzpicture}\draw[blue, line width=1] (0,0) -- (3,4) node[midway,above,xshift=-4] {\(S\)};
                        \draw[blue, dashed] (3,4) -- (10,0);
                        \draw[blue, line width=1] (10,0) -- (0,0) node[midway,below] {\(S\)};
                        \draw[blue, line width=1] (1,0) arc (0:53.1301023542:1) node[midway,right,xshift=2,yshift=2] {\(A\)};
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                      </latex-image>
                    </image>
                  </li>
              </ul>
              </p>
          </li>
          <li>
              <p>Three sides.</p>
              <p>
                <ul>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      <em>Side-Side-Side (SSS)</em>: All three sides of the triangle are known.
                    </p>
                    <image xml:id="fig-triangle-side-side-side">
                      <latex-image>
                        \begin{tikzpicture}
                        \draw[blue, line width=1] (0,0) -- (3,4) node[midway,above,xshift=-4] {\(S\)};
                        \draw[blue, line width=1] (3,4) -- (10,0) node[midway,above,xshift=2] {\(S\)};
                        \draw[blue, line width=1] (10,0) -- (0,0) node[midway,below] {\(S\)};
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                      </latex-image>
                    </image>
                  </li>
              </ul>
              </p>
          </li>
      </ol>
    </p>
    <p>
      In this section, we explore techniques for solving triangles when provided with one side and two angles (ASA or SAA) and when given two sides along with the angle between them (SSA). Triangles falling under the categories of SAS and SSS will be discussed in more detail in the <xref ref="law_of_cosines"/>.
    </p>
  </introduction>
  <subsection xml:id="subsec-law-of-sines">
    <title>Law of Sines</title>
    <p>
      The <term>Law of Sines</term> states that for any triangle, the ratios of the lengths of the sides to the sine of their corresponding opposite angles are equal. When provided with certain information about the sides and angles of a triangle, this fundamental principle becomes a valuable tool for determining the remaining sides and angles.
    </p>
    <theorem xml:id="thm-law-of-sines">
      <title>Law of Sines</title><idx><h>law of sines</h></idx>
      <statement>
        <p>
          In triangle <m>ABC</m>, we have
          <me>
            \frac{\sin A}{a}=\frac{\sin B}{b}=\frac{\sin C}{c}
          </me>
          which may also be written in the form
          <me>
            \frac{a}{\sin A}=\frac{b}{\sin B}=\frac{c}{\sin C}
          </me>
        </p>
        <p>
          The first form is more convenient when you are trying to find an angle and the second form is more convenient when you are trying to find a side.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </theorem>
    <proof>
      <p>
        In any triangle, we can draw an <term>altitude</term>, <idx><h>altitude</h></idx> a line through a vertex and perpendicular to the side opposite the vertex.
      </p>
      <image xml:id="fig-law-of-sines-proof">
        <latex-image>
          \begin{tikzpicture}
          \draw (0,0) -- (3,4) node[midway,above] {\(b\)};
          \draw (3,4) -- (10,0) node[midway,above] {\(a\)};
          \draw (10,0) -- (0,0) node[midway,below] {\(c\)};
          \node[left] at (0,0) {\(A\)};
          \node[above] at (3,4) {\(C\)};
          \node[right] at (10,0) {\(B\)};
          \draw[dashed] (3,4) -- (3,0) node[midway,right] {\(h\)};
          \draw (3,0.5) -- (3.5,0.5) -- (3.5,0);
          \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
      </image>
      <p>
        Using the right triangles, we have <m>\sin A=\frac{h}{b}</m> and <m>\sin B=\frac{h}{a}</m>. Solving both equations for <m>h</m>, we get <m>h=b\sin A</m> and <m>h=a\sin B</m>. Since these equations both equal <m>h</m>, we can now set them equal to each other.
        <me>
          b\sin A = a\sin B
        </me>
      </p>
      <p>
        Dividing both sides by <m>ab</m>, we get
        <me>
          \frac{\sin A}{a}=\frac{\sin B}{b}
        </me>
      </p>
      <p>
        Using the same method, we can get
        <me>
          \frac{\sin A}{a}=\frac{\sin C}{c}\mbox{ and } \frac{\sin B}{b}=\frac{\sin C}{c}
        </me>
      </p>
      <p>
        Putting these together, we get
        <me>
          \frac{\sin A}{a}=\frac{\sin B}{b}=\frac{\sin C}{c}
        </me>
      </p>
    </proof>
    <remark>
      <p>
        When solving triangles, it is often useful to use the fact that the sum of the angles in a triangle equals <m>180^{\circ}</m>. That is,
      <me>
        A+B+C=180^{\circ}
      </me>
      </p>
    </remark>
  </subsection>
  <subsection xml:id="subsec-solving-asa-triangles">
    <title>Solving ASA Triangles</title>
    <example xml:id="example-using-law-of-sines-asa">
      <title>Using Law of Sines (ASA)</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          The waʻa Kānehūnāmoku is returning from an afternoon sail from training students in the ways of sailing. Two observers stand 1,000 feet apart on the shore at Kāne`ohe Bay spot Kānehūnāmoku. Observer <m>A</m> determines that the angle between the waʻa and Observer <m>B</m> is <m>80^{\circ}</m> while Observer <m>B</m> determines that the angle between the waʻa and Observer <m>A</m> is <m>60^{\circ}</m>. How far is Kānehūnāmoku from each observer and what is the angle formed by the two observers (round your answer to the nearest foot)?
        </p>
        <image xml:id="fig-example-using-law-of-sines-asa" width="80%">
          <latex-image>
            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.6]
            \draw (-2,0) -- (12,0) node[midway,below,xshift=-4] {\(c=1,000\)};
            \draw (0,0) -- (80:13.47) node[midway,left,xshift=-2] {\(b\)};
            \draw (10,0) -- (80:13.47) node[midway,right,xshift=2] {\(a\)};
            \draw pic at (80:13.47) {waa-single-side={waacolor}{0}{0.15}};
            \node[below left] at 
            (0,0) {\(A\)};
            \node[below right] at (10,0) {\(B\)};
            \node[left,yshift=-6] at (80:13.47) {\(C\)};
            \draw (1.5,0) arc (0:80:1.5) node[midway,right,xshift=2] {\(80^{\circ}\)};
            \draw (8.5,0) arc (180:120:1.5) node[midway,left,yshift=1.5] {\(60^{\circ}\)};
            \draw (80:11.97) arc (260:300:1.5);
            \end{tikzpicture}
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          In this triangle, we know the values of two angles and the side between them, so we have an Angle-Side-Angle (ASA) triangle. We know that <m>A+B+C=180^{\circ}</m>. So <m>80^{\circ}+60^{\circ}+C=140^{\circ}+C=180^{\circ}</m> so <m>C=40^{\circ}</m>. To solve for <m>a</m>, we will use the Law of Sines. Either form for the Law of Sines can be used to solve this problem, but since we are solving for a side, it would be easier and require fewer steps if we use the second form for the Law of Sines.
          <md>
            <mrow>\frac{a}{\sin A}\amp =\amp \frac{c}{\sin C}</mrow>
            <mrow>\frac{a}{\sin 80^{\circ}}\amp =\amp \frac{1,000}{\sin 40^{\circ}}</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
        <p>
          Multiplying both sides by <m>\sin 80^{\circ}</m>,
          <me>
            a=\frac{1,000\sin 80^{\circ}}{\sin 40^{\circ}}\approx1,532\mbox{ ft}
          </me>.
        </p>
        <p>
          To solve for <m>b</m>, we have two options to use for the Law of Sines
          <me>
            \frac{b}{\sin B}=\frac{a}{\sin A}\qquad\mbox{or} \qquad\frac{b}{\sin B}=\frac{c}{\sin C}
          </me>
        </p>
        <p>
          Because our answer for <m>a</m> was rounded, using the first option may lead to rounding errors so it is best to use the second option because it has known values that we were originally given in the problem (<m>c=1,000</m>). Thus we will use
          <me>
            \frac{b}{\sin B}=\frac{c}{\sin C}
          </me>
        </p>
        <p>
          So we get
          <me>
            b=\frac{c\sin B}{\sin C}=\frac{1,000\sin 60^{\circ}}{\sin 40^{\circ}}\approx1,347\mbox{ ft}
          </me>
        </p>
        <p>
          Thus Kānehūnāmoku is 1,347 feet from Observer A and 1,532 feet from Observer B, and the angle between the two observers is <m>40^{\circ}</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
  </subsection>
  <subsection xml:id="subsec-solving-saa-triangles">
    <title>Solving SAA Triangles</title>
    <example xml:id="example-using-law-of-sines-saa">
      <title>Using Law of Sines (SAA)</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          For the triangle shown below with <m>A=120^{\circ}</m>, <m>C=20^{\circ}</m>, and <m>a=5</m>, find the remaining sides. Round your answer to two decimal places.
        </p>
        <image xml:id="fig-example-using-law-of-sines-saa" width="80%">
          <latex-image>
            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=2]
            \draw (0,0) -- (1.97,0) node[midway,below] {\(c\)};
            \draw (0,0) -- (120:3.71) node[midway,below,xshift=-3] {\(b\)};
            \draw (1.97,0) -- (120:3.71) node[midway,right,xshift=5] {\(a=5\)};
            \node[above] at (120:3.71) {\(C\)};
            \node[below left] at (0,0) {\(A\)};
            \node[below right] at (1.97,0) {\(B\)};
            \draw (0.5,0) arc (0:120:0.5) node[midway,xshift=8,yshift=6] {\(120^{\circ}\)};
            \draw (120:3.21) arc (-60:-40:0.5) node[right,xshift=6] {\(20^{\circ}\)};
            \end{tikzpicture}
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          In this triangle, we know the values of one side and two consecutive angles, so we have a Side-Angle-Angle (SAA) triangle. The third angle can be calculated by subtracting the known angles from <m>180^{\circ}</m>.
          <me>
            B=180^{\circ}-A-C=180^{\circ}-120^{\circ}-20^{\circ}=40^{\circ}
          </me>
        </p>
        <p>
          Using the first form of the Law of Sines
          <me>
            \frac{b}{\sin B}=\frac{a}{\sin A}\qquad\mbox{and} \qquad\frac{c}{\sin C}=\frac{a}{\sin A}
          </me>
          we have
          <me>
            b=\frac{a\sin B}{\sin A}=\frac{5\sin40^{\circ}}{\sin120^{\circ}}\approx3.71
          </me>
          and
          <me>
            c=\frac{a\sin C}{\sin A}=\frac{5\sin20^{\circ}}{\sin120^{\circ}}\approx1.97
          </me>
          
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
  </subsection>
  <subsection xml:id="subsec-solving-ssa-triangles">
    <title>Solving SSA Triangles: The Ambiguous Case</title>
    <p>
      Although the Law of Sines can be used to solve oblique triangles, there may be cases that would give us one triangle, two triangles, or even no solution. Such cases are known as the <em>ambiguous case</em>. This occurs when we know two sides and an angle that is opposite to one of the given sides.
    </p>
    <definition xml:id="def-ambiguous-case">
      <title>The Ambiguous Case</title><idx><h>ambiguous case</h></idx>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Consider a triangle where <m>a</m>, <m>b</m>, and <m>A</m> are given. The altitude is <m>h=b\sin A</m>. Then we have the following possibilities
        </p>
        <p>
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>A</m> is acute and <m>a\lt h=b\sin A</m>: <em>No triangle</em>
              </p>
              <image xml:id="fig-ssa-case1">
                <latex-image>
                  \begin{tikzpicture}
                  \draw[blue,line width=1,dashed] (0,0) -- (5.5,0);
                  \draw[blue,line width=1] (0,0) -- (4,3) node[midway,left,xshift=-4,yshift=3] {\(b\)};
                  \draw[blue] (0.75,0) arc (0:36.8698976458:0.75);
                  \node[blue,below] at (0,0) {\(A\)};
                  \node[blue,above] at (4,3) {\(C\)};
                  \draw (3.75,0) -- (3.75,0.25) -- (4,0.25);
                  \draw[dashed] (4,0) -- (4,3) node[midway,right] {\(h\)};
                  \draw[red,line width=1] (4,3) -- (5,1) node[midway,right] {\(a\)};
                  \draw (5,1) arc (296.565:285:2.2360679775);
                  \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
              </image>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>A</m> is acute and <m>a=h=b\sin A</m>: <em>One right triangle</em>
              </p>
              <image xml:id="fig-ssa-case2">
                <latex-image>
                  \begin{tikzpicture}
                  \draw[blue,line width=1,dashed] (0,0) -- (5,0);
                  \draw[blue,line width=1] (0,0) -- (4,3) node[midway,left,xshift=-4,yshift=3] {\(b\)};
                  \draw[blue] (0.75,0) arc (0:36.8698976458:0.75);
                  \node[blue,below] at (0,0) {\(A\)};
                  \node[blue,above] at (4,3) {\(C\)};
                  \draw (3.75,0) -- (3.75,0.25) -- (4,0.25);
                  \draw[blue,line width=1] (4,0) -- (4,3) node[midway,right] {\(h=a\)};
                  \draw (4,0) arc (270:300:2.2360679775);
                  \draw (4,0) arc (270:240:2.2360679775);
                  \node[blue,below] at (4,0) {\(B\)};
                  \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
              </image>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>A</m> is acute and <m>h=b\sin A\lt a\lt b</m>:  <em>Two triangles</em> (<m>\Delta ACB_1</m> and <m>\Delta ACB_2</m>)
              </p>
              <image xml:id="fig-ssa-case3">
                <latex-image>
                  \begin{tikzpicture}
                  \draw[blue,line width=1,dashed] (0,0) -- (6.5,0);
                  \draw[blue,line width=1] (0,0) -- (4,3) node[midway,left,xshift=-4,yshift=3] {\(b\)};
                  \draw[blue] (0.75,0) arc (0:36.8698976458:0.75);
                  \node[blue,below] at (0,0) {\(A\)};
                  \node[blue,above] at (4,3) {\(C\)};
                  \draw (3.75,0) -- (3.75,0.25) -- (4,0.25);
                  \draw[dashed] (4,0) -- (4,3) node[midway,right] {\(h\)};
                  \draw[red,line width=1] (4,3) -- (2,0) node[midway,right] {\(a_2\)};
                  \draw[red,line width=1] (4,3) -- (6,0) node[midway,right] {\(a_1\)};
                  \node[red,below] at (2,0) {\(B_2\)};
                  \node[red,below] at (6,0) {\(B_1\)};
                  \draw (6,0) arc (303.69:313.69:3.60555127546);
                  \draw (6,0) arc (303.69:226.31:3.60555127546);
                  \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
              </image>
              <sidebyside>
                <image xml:id="fig-ssa-case3a">
                  <latex-image>
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                    \draw[blue,line width=1,dashed] (0,0) -- (6,0);
                    \draw[dashed] (6,0) -- (6.25,0);
                    \draw[blue,line width=1] (0,0) -- (4,3) node[midway,left,xshift=-4,yshift=3] {\(b\)};
                    \draw[blue] (0.75,0) arc (0:36.8698976458:0.75);
                    \node[blue,below] at (0,0) {\(A\)};
                    \node[blue,above] at (4,3) {\(C\)};
                    \draw (3.75,0) -- (3.75,0.25) -- (4,0.25);
                    \draw[dashed] (4,0) -- (4,3) node[midway,right] {\(h\)};
                    \draw[blue,line width=1] (4,3) -- (6,0) node[midway,right] {\(a_1\)};
                    \node[blue,below] at (6,0) {\(B_1\)};
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                  </latex-image>
                </image>
                <image xml:id="fig-ssa-case3b">
                  <latex-image>
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
